				<p><b>Isabel Bayrakdarian</b></p>

				<p>In 1997 Isabel Bayrakadarian received an honours degree in biomedical engineering from the University of Toronto. That same year she was a winner of the Metropolitan Opera National Council Auditions. Luckily for music lovers she chose the latter milestone upon which to base a career. Since then she has become an eagerly anticipated visitor to opera houses and concert halls the world over and is admired equally for her stunning stage presence and exceptional musicality.</p>

				<p>In 1999 she scored a notable success in the Lyric Opera of Chicago&rsquo;s world premiere production of William Bolcom&rsquo;s <i>A View from the Bridge</i> and in the following year won first prize in Pl&aacute;cido Domingo&rsquo;s Operalia competition. She launched 2002 with her San Francisco Opera debut, as Valencienne in <i>The Merry Widow</i>, and closed it with her Metropolitan Opera debut, in the New York premiere of Bolcom&rsquo;s opera. Later, Mozart became a specialty: Zerlina in <i>Don Giovanni</i> (New York, Houston, Salzburg), Susanna in <i>Le nozze di Figaro</i> (Los Angeles, London), and Pamina in <i>The Magic Flute</i> (New York, Toronto). Her roles at her home-base theatre, Toronto&rsquo;s Canadian Opera Company, have ranged from Gluck&rsquo;s <i>Euridice</i> to Debussy&rsquo;s <i>M&eacute;lisande</i> to Poulenc&rsquo;s Blanche in <i>Dialogues des Carm&eacute;lites</i>&thinsp;&mdash;&thinsp;and away from home she&rsquo;s shone as Monteverdi&rsquo;s <i>Poppea</i> in Barcelona, Handel&rsquo;s <i>Romilda</i> (Serse) in Dresden, and Jan&aacute;ček&rsquo;s <i>Vixen</i> in New York, Florence, and the Saito Kinen Festival in Matsumoto, Japan.</p>

				<p>Also an active concertizer, Isabel has appeared with the premier orchestras of numerous North American and European cities with such eminent conductors as Seiji Ozawa, Michael Tilson Thomas, Christoph Eschenbach, Nikolaus Harnoncourt, James Levine, Anne Manson, Bramwell Tovey and Richard Bradshaw. Her versatility is further reflected in being the featured vocalist on, amongst others, the soundtracks of the blockbuster film <i>The Lord of The Rings: The Two Towers</i> and Atom Egoyan&rsquo;s Ararat. Additional interesting musical explorations have included singing the national anthem at the Closing Ceremony of the Pan Am Games in Toronto in front of over 50,000 people and broadcast live to millions around the world.</p>

				<p>Bayrakdarian is the winner of four consecutive Juno Awards for Best Classical Album (Vocal). However, her happiest collaborations, personal and professional, have involved the Armenian-Canadian pianist and composer Serouj Kradjian, her frequent accompanist and arranger and (not least) her husband and the father of their two young children. Their Nonesuch CD <i>Gomidas Songs</i> promoted and popularized the work of Armenian composer Gomidas Vartabed, earning them a Grammy nomination in 2009. Their collaboration on <i>Troubadour &amp; the Nightingale</i> (2013) with the Manitoba Chamber Orchestra and Anne Manson received yet another Juno nomination.</p>

				<p>Other recordings with orchestra include Henryk G&oacute;recki&rsquo;s Symphony No. 3 with John Axelrod conducting the Danish National Symphony Orchestra, released on the Sony Classical label. Her latest recording <i>Il Tramonto</i>, with the Orchestre Symphonique de Laval and Alain Trudel was released in September 2015, on the ATMA Classique label.</p>

				<p>Ms Bayrakdarian has received many awards, including the Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee and the Diamond Jubilee Medals. In 2015, she was awarded Doctor of Letters, <i>honoris causa</i>, by Canada&rsquo;s Wilfrid Laurier University.</p>

				<p><b>Roberto Sierra</b></p>

				<p>For more than three decades the works of American composer Roberto Sierra have been part of the repertoire of many leading orchestras, ensembles and festivals in the USA and Europe. At the inaugural concert of the 2002 world-renowned Proms in London, his Fandangos was performed by the BBC Symphony Orchestra in a concert that was broadcast by both the BBC Radio and Television throughout the UK and Europe. Many major American and European orchestras and international ensembles have commissioned and performed his works. Among those institutions are the orchestras of Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Atlanta, New Mexico, Houston, Minnesota, Dallas, Detroit, San Antonio and Phoenix, as well as the American Composers Orchestra, the New York Philharmonic, Los Angeles Philharmonic, National Symphony Orchestra, Royal Scottish National Orchestra, the Tonhalle Orchestra of Zurich, and the Spanish orchestras of Madrid, Galicia, Castilla y Le&oacute;n and  Barcelona.</p>

				<p>In 2003 Sierra was awarded the Academy Award in Music by the American Academy of Arts and Letters. The award states: &ldquo;Roberto Sierra writes brilliant music, mixing fresh and personal melodic lines with sparkling harmonies and striking rhythms&thinsp;&hellip;&thinsp;&rdquo; He has served as Composer-in-Residence with the Milwaukee Symphony Orchestra, The Philadelphia Orchestra, The Puerto Rico Symphony Orchestra and New Mexico Symphony. In 2010 he was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.</p>

				<p>The composer&rsquo;s music may be heard on CDs issued by Naxos, EMI, UMG&rsquo;s EMARCY, New World Records, Albany Records, Koch, New Albion, Koss Classics, BMG, Fleur de Son and other labels.  Sierra has been nominated twice for a Grammy under best contemporary composition category, first in 2009 for <i>Missa Latina</i> (Naxos), and in 2014 for his Sinfonia No. 4 (Naxos).</p>

				<p>Roberto Sierra was born in 1953 in Vega Baja, Puerto Rico, and studied composition both in Puerto Rico and Europe, where one of his teachers was Gy&ouml;rgy Ligeti at the Hochschule f&uuml;r Musik in Hamburg, Germany.</p>

				<p><b>Boyd MacKenzie</b></p>

				<p>Boyd MacKenzie is a violinist with the Manitoba Chamber Orchestra, and was also a long-time member of the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra and MusikBarock Ensemble. He serves as the contractor and concert manager of the Manitoba Chamber Orchestra and manages the MCO&rsquo;s Minstrel booking agency. Boyd has composed a number of scores for film and television, and has arranged music for a variety of ensembles. He is a founding member of the Cambrian Quartet, which has performed throughout Manitoba, as well as in the U.S. and England. A graduate of Brandon University&rsquo;s School of Music, he studied with Francis Chaplin, Joel Hekester (former concertmaster of the Concertgebouw Orchestra of Amsterdam) and Paul Makanowitsky (Meadowmount School of Music, New York). Boyd performed with the Utrecht Symphony Orchestra, Netherlands, before returning to Canada and beginning work with the Manitoba Chamber Orchestra.</p>

